SIMPLE: flock
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flock
<hw>Flock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>flocc</ets>
flock, company; akin to Icel. <ets>flokkr</ets> crowd, Sw.
<ets>flock</ets>, Dan. <ets>flok</ets>; prob. orig. used of flows, and
akin to E. <ets>fly</ets>. See <er>Fly</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
company or collection of living creatures; -- especially applied to
sheep and birds, rarely to persons or (except in the plural) to cattle
and other large animals; <as>as, a <ex>flock</ex> of ravenous
fowl</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heathen . . . came to Nicanor by <qex>flocks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Macc. xiv. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A Christian church or congregation; considered in
their relation to the pastor, or minister in charge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As half amazed, half frighted all his <qex>flock</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flock
<hw>Flock</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Flocked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flocking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To gather in companies or
crowds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Friends daily <qex>flock</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flocking fowl</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
greater scaup duck.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flock
<hw>Flock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To flock to; to crowd.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good fellows, trooping, <qex>flocked</qex> me so.</q>
<rj><qau>Taylor (1609).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Flock
<hw>Flock</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>flokke</ets>; cf. D.
<ets>vlok</ets>, G. <ets>flocke</ets>, OHG. <ets>floccho</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fl⟦omac⟧ki</ets>, perh. akin to E. <ets>flicker</ets>,
<ets>flacker</ets>, or cf. L. <ets>floccus</ets>, F.
<ets>floc</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A lock of wool or
hair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I prythee, Tom, beat Cut's saddle, put a few <qex>flocks</qex> in
the point [pommel].</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Woolen or cotton refuse (<pos>sing. ⟦or⟧ pl.</pos>),
old rags, etc., reduced to a degree of fineness by machinery, and used
for stuffing unpholstered furniture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Very fine, sifted, woolen refuse, especially that
from shearing the nap of cloths, used as a coating for wall paper to
give it a velvety or clothlike appearance; also, the dust of vegetable
fiber used for a similar purpose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flock bed</b></col>, <cd>a bed filled with flocks or
locks of coarse wool, or pieces of cloth cut up fine.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Once a
<xex>flock bed</xex>, but repaired with straw.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Pope.</au> --
<col><b>Flock paper</b></col>, <cd>paper coated with flock fixed with
glue or size.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Flock
<hw>Flock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To coat with flock, as wall paper;
to roughen the surface of (as glass) so as to give an appearance of
being covered with fine flock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flockling</ent>⟦br⟧
